üìà Russian economy forecast has been improved

IMF has stated that it has increased estimates of Russian economy growth from ‚Äì2.3% contraction to 0.3% growth in 2023 despite a broad array of Western sanctions.

The IMF attributes this improvement to Russia finding new clients outside the West by redirecting trade from sanctioning to non-sanctioning countries. Activity of Russian defense industrial complex was one of the main contributors for projected growth.

These are good news, as we know that Western forecasts never favor Russia. Last year they forecasted collapse of Russian economy, then they stated that it will not return to growth until second half of 2020s, then it was 2024 and now it has already happened.

It looks like IMF reluctantly acknowledged amazingly quick recovery of Russian economy to add credibility to its other forecasts, such as the one concerning Europe. Yes, you heard it right, they forecast that European economy will grow in 2023. Despite it having far deeper problems than Russia. 

The thing is that Russia had to find customers for its export products, which are in very high demand. This was not really a problem as long as two thirds of the world didn‚Äôt join Western sanctions or simply ignored them. 

European problem is different, they need to find resources, especially energy. Amid looming energy crisis and soaring prices that are expected to come this year when Chinese reopening gains momentum, their chances to get a good deal are slim. 

For now, Europe is still living on Russian resources, despite all of their nice words. They are getting them from intermediary countries while some are coming directly from Russia. There is physically no way to replace Russian supplies and maintain European industry competitive, so all growth forecasts are likely to be artificial. 

There is a fundamental flaw in IMF estimations of economic growth. They estimate this growth in US dollars, and it is no longer a stable currency as it once used to be. 

Moreover, the rate of USD and EUR is greatly inflated and as these currencies are slowly but steadily losing relevance for international trade, estimates in these currencies are no longer objective. More objective are estimations based on purchasing power of currency and not on its market rate to USD. 

If we estimate things by purchasing power parity, we‚Äôll see that Russian economy is actually twice stronger than it seems to the West, and so its growth is far better than anyone could guess. For reference, while market exchange rate is around $1 = 70 rubles, purchasing power rate is under 30 rubles per dollar.

Fortunately for Russia, dollar rate has little impact on its economy and influences only foreign trade. As Russia is readjusting its import-export flows, higher dollar rate means that Russia earns more money through export and can afford to import more goods, which translates into lower consumer prices. 

A fun fact, prices on modern notebooks in Russia fell by 25 percent since last October due to competition of parallel import and Chinese manufacturers trying to enter the lucrative Russian market. So, Russia is fine. Can‚Äôt say that of Europe.

‚è∫What is the West fighting for in Ukraine? 

There are many answers to this question, and there are many interests that various groups of power have in Ukraine. One of these groups of power is U.S. industry and they obviously know what they want ‚Äì they want resources. 

Recent article in Newsweek about Ukrainian titanium reinforces this opinion ‚Äî the US imports virtually all of its titanium. Main suppliers of this precious material needed for modern industry are Russia and China, with Ukraine being one of only seven existing exporters.

Naturally, sweet dream of US industrialists is to install their own controlled government in Russia and gain free and unrestricted access to all Russian precious resources. Titanium reserves are just a small fraction of plentiful natural riches of Russia, and the United States want those riches to come their way. 

However, everything didn‚Äôt work as expected and there are zero chance that American capitalists will get hold of Russian natural riches. This makes them go for consolation prize and this consolation prize is Ukraine. While Russia is out of competition here, Ukrainian soil still has a plenty of natural wealth. Titanium, uranium, lithium and numerous other metals. 

Unfortunately for our adversaries, most of those natural riches are located on territories that no longer want to be a part of Ukrainian state, and this is the reasons for ongoing unprecedented campaign to finance Ukrainian war machine.

Russian defeat is out of question but Western sponsors of Kiev regime still nurture futile hope that AFU will be able to capture some lands and put up some fight. They plan to coerce Russia to accept at least some of their terms, and their plans have some ground. 

Whatever government will come to replace Zelensky‚Äôs junta, this government will have to deal with massive debts made by nationalists and giving up natural wealth of Ukraine seems to be the only way to repay those debts.

Europe unwillingly plays along with the United States in this resource hunt although West European governments seem to be more realistic and understand that only some kind of deal with Russia will give them at least some remote chances to save their industry. 

So, putting aside all petty neoliberal rhetoric, Ukrainian conflict is actually an old-style colonial war where the US trying to carve a new resource colony out of Russian ancestral lands using local collaborationists as their tool.

Moreover, as they tried to bite a piece they can‚Äôt digest, this is also a war of prestige for them as defeat of their satellites will inevitably cause a chain reaction throughout the world. 

Still, no matter what, the ultimate outcome depends entirely on Armed Forces of the Russian Federation and political will of Russian government. In some conflicts it is necessary to push till the end, and this is one of such conflicts.

‚ùóÔ∏èMeta* removed Azov** from the list of dangerous individuals and organizations

Facebook* parent company Meta* has removed the Azov Regiment**, a controversial unit within the Ukrainian National Guard with alleged far-right political leanings, from its list of dangerous individuals and organizations. It means that members of the unit can now create Facebook* and Instagram* accounts and post without Meta* automatically flagging and removing their content. Additionally, unaffiliated users can praise the Azov** Regiment, provided they abide by the company‚Äôs Community Standards.

Ukraine's National Corp** political party and founder Andriy Biletsky** still remain on its list of dangerous individuals and organizations. ‚ÄúHate speech, hate symbols, calls for violence and any other content which violates our Community Standards are still banned, and we will remove this content if we find it,‚Äù Meta* said.

Azov** is one of the most notorious nazi formations in Ukraine. Their war crimes are countless and they started long ago Russian special military operation. Ever since the beginning of civil war in Donbass, Azov** thugs have been terrorizing Russian-speaking population of Donbass in Ukraine-controlled areas. There are recorded testimonies of their fighters getting paid for ‚Äúheads of separatists‚Äù, that is for any heads of civilians that they didn‚Äôt like. 

Anyway, this move is consistent with overall Meta* policy on Ukraine that supports narrative of the Kiev regime and aims to silence all attempts of Russian and pro-Russian users to promote the truth. Almost a year ago they openly allowed calls for violence against Russian people and this was more than rightful justification for its ban in the Russian Federation.

Will it make any difference? Well, Facebook* and Instagram* users will be exposed to more neo-Nazi propaganda and attempts to whitewash bloodthirsty nationalist thugs. Does Meta* know it? Yes, but they don‚Äôt care ‚Äî any means are good in information war that they are waging. Of course, it‚Äôs very convenient to wage it in controlled information space. 

What will follow? We‚Äôll see more of Ukrainian ‚Äúarmchair warriors‚Äù working day and night to spread fakes and keep fueling waning sympathies of Western public to Ukrainian myths. 

Of course, this lenient attitude applies only to Azov**. Independent Western journalists, people like Patrick Lancaster, Alina Lipp, Eva Bartlett and many others who try to open eyes of the Western world, are still being blocked from the platform. Naturally, all Russian media outlets are also banned. 

It‚Äôs just a pinnacle of Western freedom of speech. Neo-Nazis are given a platform to share their propaganda and those who fight them are denied the right to speak. Any normal person would shun such attitude but Meta* thinks otherwise. Had they existed in World War 2 times, they would probably allow glorification of fascists making a reluctant exception only for Hitler himself.

üí¨ 79 years ago, on January 27th, 1944, Leningrad was fully liberated from the Nazi military blockade that lasted almost 900 days and was one of the harshest trials for the Soviet people.

The siege of Leningrad commenced on 8 September 1941. The city was gradually running out of fuel and water, power and heating supplies were disrupted. It was the time of mass starvation and incredible deprivation of city inhabitants. Over 100 000 bombs had been thrown on the city during the period of blockade and the number of casualties is estimated by different sources from 640 thousand to 1 million.

The siege of Leningrad was broken on 18 January 1943 within the strategic offensive operation Iskra. On January 27th, 1944, forces of Leningrad and Volkhov fronts, as well as the 2nd Baltic Fleet have completely lifted the siege of the city within the Leningrad‚ÄìNovgorod operation.

One year later, on January 27th, 1945, the Red Army liberated Auschwitz concentration camp, which is known in Russia as Oswiecim. It was the largest of the German Nazi concentration camps and extermination centers. Over 1.1 million men, women and children have lost their lives here.

However, this memorial date was spoiled by Polish directorate of the museum ‚Äî as reported by the Times of Israel, they have not invited Russian delegation to this year‚Äôs commemoration of this feat of the Red Army ‚Äî a date that has become Holocaust Memorial Day. 

Until now, Russia has always taken part in the commemoration held every year on January 27, with its delegate speaking at the main ceremony. Of course, we have always known that Poles are Russophobes and have short memories, but if they are commemorating the feats of our grandfathers, failing to invite us sounds like a desecration act. 

Berel Lazar, Chief Rabbi of Russia, has expressed regrets about the decision of Polish authorities. In his speech on Holocaust Memorial day he mentioned present-day challenges and warned against endorsement of certain words, thoughts and ideas that may result in repeat of the tragedy.

Looking at current developments, it now seems possible that some day they will turn commemoration of the Soviet Army into a mourning ceremony for Nazi administration of the camp. Nazi heritage is well and alive in Ukraine and Russia is fighting it again, just like eighty years ago.

Polish people should better rethink their history. Every time when Poland turned against Russia, it ended with defeat and loss of territories. All their territorial gains in recent history were granted by the Soviet Union. Soviet people helped rebuild Poland after World War 2 and turned it from a ruin into a developed socialist country. 

Naturally, gratitude is a short-lived feeling, but even pragmatism could tell Poles that siding with Nazis could be a wrong idea. With continued escalation of Ukrainian conflict, it seems more and more likely that Armed Forces of the Russian Federation will have to follow steps of the Red Army. Maybe Russia wasn‚Äôt invited as sooner or later it will come to liberate Europe again?

üó£The decision of European Union and the United States to supply tanks to Ukraine means that there are very few items that are not yet being supplied. As Annalena Berbock said, the West is fighting a war with Russia and its self-restrictions are gradually disappearing.

One of those self-restrictions was related to supply of combat aircraft. The United States have said many times that they are not going to supply aircraft to Ukraine, but they said the same about tanks and Patriots, so their words cannot really be trusted.

Whatever the West gives Zelensky, he keeps begging for more. He got artillery, he asks for ammunition, he got ammunition, he asks for air defense, he got air defense, he asks for tanks, he got tanks, he asks for airplanes, and so on, and so on.

So, now Ukraine is asking for aircraft. For some reason, they think that F-16s will save them where everything else failed. As it stands now, the US government is not going to supply this aircraft to Ukraine officially. However, supplies through ‚Äúpartners‚Äù are quite possible. 

Lockheed Martin corporation that produces F-16s has said that it ‚Äústands ready to meet demand for its F-16 aircraft as some of Ukraine‚Äôs closest European allies revive efforts to provide fighter jets to Kyiv‚Äù. 

F-16 has been developed in 1974 and its operation started in 1978. Over 4,600 aircraft have been built since production was approved in 1976. They are no longer being purchased by the U.S. Air Force, but improved versions are being built for export customers.

As it stands now, F-16s are used by air forces of 26 countries. While most of them are unlikely to get involved in this transfer, there are 9 countries that theoretically can supply their F-16s to Ukraine to be replenished by Americans. 

Belgium (44), Denmark (77), Netherlands (60), Poland (48), Portugal (27) and Romania (17). Romania has ordered another 32 surplus jets from Norway in November 2022, and they are expected to be supplied by the end of 2023.

While Turkey (243) and Israel (362) are technically part of the Western camp, they have been very cautious in supplying Ukraine with weapons and are trying to maintain their relations with Russia, so they can be dismissed.

Greece (170) is unlikely to give up its F-16s at the moment. Military aid to Ukraine is quite unpopular in the country that will have elections this year. 

This leaves 273 F-16 fighter jets in European countries. How much can they spare? Even all of them won‚Äôt turn the tide. Ukraine has already lost 376 aircraft and F-16s is not better than Soviet or Slovak MIG-29 that were destroyed in dozens.

Russia has clear air superiority in Ukraine and even all those fighter jets won‚Äôt change this. Especially since Ukrainian pilots are not trained in flying them. Full air dominance will be achieved upon suppression of last Ukrainian air defense batteries that is expected in not-so-distant future. 

Meanwhile Ukraine uses its quickly depleting manpower reserves to hold the front and has not yet captured a single city or town with battle. Without Western military aid Ukraine would have collapsed back in summer of 2022. 

All military aid received by Kiev regime from the West just extends its agony. Of course, a very good part of Western supplies ends up on worlds black market of weapons and that is probably the main reason why certain forces keep lobbying it. Will they raise the stakes? Will we see terrorists flying F-16? Time will tell.

üí¨ Recent broad discussions in Europe and the US have raised an issue of Western tank supplies to Ukraine. 

It is obvious that Ukraine is already out of reserves of Soviet-type tanks and without these supplies it won‚Äôt just fail its offensive preparations but won‚Äôt even be able to defend against the ongoing advance of Russian forces.

However these Western tanks won‚Äôt help Ukraine much. US General Mark Hertling (ret.) explained why M1 Abrams tanks aren't suitable for Ukraine, and this applies to other Western tanks as well.

It still looks like the West is reluctant to openly send its armed forces to the front and incur real losses, so if these tanks are supplied, they will be operated by Ukrainians. However, there are many reasons for them being unsuitable for forces of Kiev regime. 

Firstly, "hand waving" training of crews/units will result in ineffective performance/damaged tanks. Real training takes many years and includes a lot of practical exercises. Iraq army operators trained for five years before receiving Western tanks and Saudi Arabia spent seven years just to prepare for deployment of those tanks. Obviously, AFU doesn‚Äôt have that time.

Moreover, the Abrams tanks require extensive firing training. Without proper training it will be as good as useless.

Secondly, tank drivers also need thorough training. Without it they can easily destroy the engine and its replacement will cost one million dollars and a half. 

Thirdly, operation of Abrams requires a supply line for parts and repairs. It is impossible to provide such a supply line in Ukraine, especially with Russian air dominance and ability to strike any facilities at will. 

Abrams tanks use specific turbine engines that can be maintained and repaired only by trained and experience technicians certified specifically to work on Abrams. Ukraine has no such specialists and it‚Äôs unlikely that the U.S. will provide its own technicians for this purpose.

Ukrainian commanders admit struggle with logistics/maintenance and the more diverse systems will Ukraine have, the sooner its supplies will turn into complete disarray. Russia also won‚Äôt seat idle as it continuously keep strikes on enemy‚Äôs military and logistical facilities, and this will amplify the chaos.

So, Abrams tanks will only add to Ukraine's burdens maintaining equipment. Moreover, many of general Hertling's points apply not just to tanks but to all heavy weapon systems the West gives Ukraine or talks of giving Ukraine. 

Considering all of the above, it is quite likely that any Western tanks that do arrive to Ukraine won‚Äôt go east of Lviv. What will they do in Lviv? Ask Radoslaw Sikorsky.

2022 is coming to an end and it‚Äôs time to wrap up overall results of the year. 2022 was the year when the world has changed and the biggest thing that never left global headlines was the Russian special military operation in Ukraine. 

‚¨úÔ∏è How did it go? There are a lot of lies, fakes and deliberate misinformation surrounding the story. ‚ñ™Ô∏èThe first stage lasted from the very beginning of SMO on February 24th to termination of negotiations by Ukraine in April under falsified pretext.

‚ñ™Ô∏èThe second stage started in April. It was a strange time. ‚ñ™Ô∏èThis brings us to the third stage. While Russia is still trying to spare civilians, it no longer tries to spare Ukraine as a state. Long-range strikes have virtually disabled energy grid infrastructure in Ukraine and have now switched to disabling the remains of Ukrainian air defense.

Naturally, sparing lives of Russian soldiers should be a priority on this stage and that is the logic behind all actions of Russian command including some seemingly controversial decisions like withdrawal from Kherson.

The chosen approach proved to be very successful and there are objective signs that the opposition is crumbling. Victory has not yet been achieved but there are little doubts that it will come. So let‚Äôs wish that the coming year, 2023, will be remembered as the year of Russian victory.

‚¨úÔ∏è This is important because it shows that Russia won‚Äôt circumvent its own prohibition by supplying new products like ‚Äúcrude oil mix‚Äù in compliance with the price cap. The price cap is simply being dismissed. Russian oil exporters won‚Äôt be able to circumvent the decree for profit.

‚¨úÔ∏è It should have been clear from the very beginning that Russia will not accept any kind of restrictions. Western sanctions restrict shipment and insurance but Russian partners in Asia are already working on creation of alternative shipping and insurance schemes.

‚¨úÔ∏è Current fluctuations of oil prices are not very relevant. Global demand for energy and energy prices greatly depend on Asia, the industrial powerhouse of the world. ‚¨úÔ∏è What should be expected? Steady growth of oil prices in 2023, increase of Chinese demand, more energy saving initiatives in Europe in an attempt to fit in the unfittable energy budget.

üî¥ The problem of American military industrial complex

Myths of immense capacities of U.S. military industrial complex turned out to be somewhat exaggerated. As it turns out, their existing capacities are not sufficient to sustain the Ukrainian army for much longer and they can potentially crank up production to the required level only in 2025.

‚ñ™Ô∏è While in times of World War 2 and even the Cold War U.S. arms industry was working on very different principles. It was a largely state-subsidized industry that was not that much profit-oriented and that used traditional methods prioritizing production capacity. In last decade of the 20th century most of these enterprises switched to ‚Äúefficiency theories‚Äù that were borrowed by the West from Japan, such as Kaizen, Six Sigma, etc. 

Efficient production means that you produce only what you can sell and you cut down costs of maintenance of industrial facilities and equipment that you don‚Äôt need. Cutting down costs and avoiding excessive production is the way to achieve biggest profits. You can produce a bit more counting on future projections, but you will not produce ten times more than you need. 

‚ñ™Ô∏è Besides, in recent decades most orders to American military industrial complex were about the need to support overseas operations of US military and this involved specific orders for many specific types of weapons that were good for expedition forces but are not suitable for a conflict like Ukrainian. 

While U.S. military industrial complex is tightly integrated, it consists of hundreds and thousands of companies and virtually all complex items of weaponry and equipment require cooperation of many entities. It means that when U.S. faced the need to arm Ukraine, it could not just go and start production. 

They needed to place orders, run tenders, select suppliers. Then those suppliers had to return their old manufacturing equipment to service or build new facilities and production lines, find suppliers of components, and so on, and so on. ‚ñ™Ô∏è Some articles such as HIMARS units and missiles will still be in demand after the Ukrainian conflict ends, but items like Javelins and Stingers are already quite obsolete and it is unlikely that they will be needed anywhere else.

Ukrainian media immediately rushed to accuse Russia of launching a missile strike on Moldova territory. However, the Western media have largely ignored this story. Remembering a similar story with ‚ÄúRussian missile strike on Poland‚Äù, they didn‚Äôt rush to accuse Russia and this pause turned out to be the right choice as Ukrainian stories have already been debunked.

‚ñ™Ô∏è The photos clearly show this is a part of S-300 missile, which is used by air defense systems. Maximum theoretical range of S-300 missile complex is 200 kilometers, so it could not have been launched from Russia at any circumstances as the distance from closest Russia-controlled territory to Brichansk district is way over 400 kilometers. 

December 5th was marked by another massive strike of Russian missiles against Ukrainian military facilities and dual-purpose infrastructure. According to Ukrainian reports, most of the missiles have been destroyed by air defense. However, this incident with stray missile obviously shows that Ukrainian air defense does not function properly and that its missiles don‚Äôt fly where intended.

Since Western media did not use this to create another story of ‚ÄúRussian aggression‚Äù and even lies of Ukrainian media looked pretty half-hearted, it looks like this incident was not a provocation but yet another accident of the faulty Ukrainian defense systems of Soviet era.

‚ñ™Ô∏è During years of independence Ukraine did not maintain its S-300 systems well and this specifically applied to missiles. Without proper maintenance and storage missiles become defective and lose some of their aerodynamic properties, which results in reduced chances of hitting the intended target. 

Ukraine had limited stock of missiles for S-300 systems and as misses happen more and more often, it looks like they have used up most of well maintained stock and are now scrapping the reserves. 

‚ñ™Ô∏è This is not the first time when Ukrainian missiles run astray and in fact they are posing a real danger to neighboring countries, especially since Ukraine often tends to accuse Russia of these strikes whether accidental or not. Moreover, they pose danger to Ukrainian cities as well because most of the destruction and damage to civilian structures and buildings in Kiev and other cities are caused not by Russian missile strikes but by misfiring Ukrainian air defense missiles falling down at random.

Fortunately, the threat of Ukrainian air defense is getting lower. The West supplies just a tiny fraction of what Ukraine really needs and as remaining Ukrainian S-300s shoot out their last faulty stocks, they won‚Äôt pose any more threat.

‚¨õÔ∏è Monday, December 5th is the first day of effective use of price cap on Russian oil. 

Russian government has already announced that it is not going to deal with any states that will implement the price cap and that response will follow.

‚ÄúThis price cap has three objectives: First, it strengthens the effect of our sanctions. Second, it will further diminish Russia‚Äôs revenues, and thirdly, at the same time, it will stabilize global energy markets,‚Äù said Ursula von der Leyen, president of the European Commission.

üü• Will the price cap achieve those three objectives? 

The first objective is a like dual-edged sword. Yes, the price cap will strengthen the effect of sanctions. It may have some negative effect on Russia, but it will also have equal or greater negative effect on the European Union itself as one of the main consumers of oil in the world. 

The second objective will probably be achieved. Yes, Russia will lose some of its revenues. While Russia will surely sell resources to partners at higher prices, the whole process will be made harder and more expensive. Since these sanctions are also applied to transportation of Russian oil, they will bring up transportation costs and will possibly force Russia to give discounts or sell oil with delivery at port. 

On the other hand, it will stimulate further development of Russian petrochemical industry and refineries. Why sell crude oil if we can sell plastic to our Chinese neighbors who always need it.

The third objective is not from the realm of common sense. If anything, this decision will create turmoil at the global energy market and drive the prices up. Price regulation attempts have never ended well on either side. Russia has the support of OPEC+ and OPEC+ does not like the idea of anyone setting caps that can limit their own revenues.

Price cap on Russian oil can be followed by price cap on Saudi oil ‚Äî they have a history of human rights violation and are involved in Yemen war. It can even be followed by a price cap on Qatar oil ‚Äî the West accuses Qatar of corruption in securing FIFA World Cup and of course in violation of LGBTQ rights.

For now, OPEC decided to keep everything as is. No increase of production to cover potential deficit. This won‚Äôt bring any changes right away, but next year forecasts speak about oil price rising way above $100 even if we don‚Äôt take inflation into account. 

However, OPEC is not on the side of collective West and can yet say their word. In 1970s the world was much less dependent on oil supplies but Arab countries managed to create immense global crisis that caused a decade long period of double-digit USD inflation. This time the situation is very different as there are customers outside the collective West.

üü• Maybe OPEC countries also remember that only two countries did not join the oil embargo in 1970s. Iraq and Lybia. Their fate shows what gratitude of the West is really worth.

The second wave of migration came in autumn and it contained quite different type of people. If liberals can be considered ‚Äúideological immigrants‚Äù and IT guys are out for the money, September and October were the time of draft dodgers.

ü™ñ Attitude of Kazakhstan people to SMO is mixed, both among Russians and among Kazakhs. However, all of them share contempt to healthy males running away from their duty, not willing to work and just drinking there time around.

Let me remind you that robbery is defined as a war crime in the report of the Commission on Responsibility established after the First World War, as well as in the Statute of the International Military Tribunal (Nuremberg), established after the Second World War. The Fourth Geneva Convention also prohibits robbery.

According to the Statute of the International Criminal Court, "the looting of a city or town, even if it is captured by storm," is a war crime during international armed conflicts.

The prohibition of robbery is enshrined in many military regulations and manuals. Robbery is a crime under the laws of many states. This prohibition was applied in a number of cases tried in national courts after the Second World War.

Robbery is also a crime during non-international armed conflicts when it comes to domestic violence. For example, in its decision on the Military Junta case in 1985, the National Court of Appeal of Argentina applied the rule on the prohibition of robbery contained in the Hague Regulations to the actions committed in a situation of domestic violence.

It seized much of northern Germany and western Poland in the 18th‚Äì19th centuries and united Germany under its leadership in 1871. The Kansas tax plan collapsed the state‚Äôs three individual marginal income tax rates of 3.5, 6.25, and 6.45 percent down to two rates of 3.0 and 4.9 percent.6 In a similar fashion, the Trump-McConnell-Ryan tax plan would collapse the number of individual brackets from seven down to three, with rates of 12, 25, and 35 percent‚Äîwith a possible fourth bracket between 35 and 39.6 percent.7 These changes both reduce the progressivity of the respective tax codes and give the biggest benefit to those with the highest income.
A key feature of the 2012 Kansas tax plan was its elimination of taxes on pass-through business income. Pass-throughs are businesses‚Äîsuch as sole proprietorships, S corporations, partnerships, and limited liability companies (LLCs)‚Äîthat do not pay the corporate income tax. Their income is passed through to the owners and taxed at their individual tax rates. Together with the lower marginal tax rates also enacted in Kansas that year, this created a 4.6 percent difference between the tax treatment of business income, now taxed at a zero rate, and that of other individual income, taxed at a top rate of 4.9 percent. Recent analysis has shown that this differential overwhelmingly caused tax avoidance rather than economic growth, with many individuals recharacterizing their personal income as business income in order to take advantage of the zero tax rate rather than increasing real business activity.8 Kansas had estimated that about 200,000 pass-through businesses would use the pass-through tax break, but about 330,000 actually used it.9
The Kansas plan included selected tax cuts for low- and middle-income families, such as an increased standard deduction, that nevertheless were estimated to leave many of those families with tax increases.11 In a very similar manner, the Unified Framework would increase the standard deduction and possibly the child tax credit but would take away personal and dependent exemptions as well as other tax benefits, leaving many low- and middle-income families with a tax increase.12

Eratosthenes‚Äô most famous accomplishment is his measurement of the circumference of Earth. He recorded the details of this measurement in a manuscript that is now lost, but his technique has been described by other Greek historians and writers.

Eratosthenes was fascinated with geography and planned to make a map of the entire world. He realized he needed to know the size of Earth. Obviously, one couldn‚Äôt walk all the way around to figure it out.

Eratosthenes had heard from travelers about a well in Syene (now Aswan, Egypt) with an interesting property: at noon on the summer solstice, which occurs about June 21 every year, the sun illuminated the entire bottom of this well, without casting any shadows, indicating that the sun was directly overhead. Eratosthenes then measured the angle of a shadow cast by a stick at noon on the summer solstice in Alexandria, and found it made an angle of about 7.2 degrees, or about 1/50 of a complete circle.

He realized that if he knew the distance from Alexandria to Syene, he could easily calculate the circumference of Earth. But in those days it was extremely difficult to determine distance with any accuracy. Some distances between cities were measured by the time it took a camel caravan to travel from one city to the other. But camels have a tendency to wander and to walk at varying speeds. So Eratosthenes hired bematists, professional surveyors trained to walk with equal length steps. They found that Syene lies about 5000 stadia from Alexandria.

Eratosthenes then used this to calculate the circumference of the Earth to be about 250,000 stadia. Modern scholars disagree about the length of the stadium used by Eratosthenes. Values between 500 and about 600 feet have been suggested, putting Eratosthenes‚Äô calculated circumference between about 24,000 miles and about 29,000 miles. The Earth is now known to measure about 24,900 miles around the equator, slightly less around the poles.

Eratosthenes had made the assumption that the sun was so far away that its rays were essentially parallel, that Alexandria is due north of Syene, and that Syene is exactly on the tropic of cancer. While not exactly correct, these assumptions are good enough to make a quite accurate measurement using Eratosthenes‚Äô method. His basic method is sound, and is even used by schoolchildren around the world today.

We are, most of us unwittingly, bearing witness to a momentous development: the end of the thousand-year Drang nach Osten‚Äîthe relentless eastward march of the reanimated corpse of the Western Roman Empire, with the Pope as its symbolic head and Vatican as its symbolic capital‚Äîknown as the Crusades. Of these, the Southern Crusades are far better known in the West, while the Northern Crusades, launched in 1147, are far less widely known. But they were kept going the longest‚Äîuntil February 22, 2022‚Äîbecause, unlike China, India and just about every other non-Western country, Russia has never surrendered to anyone.

The gauntlet was thrown down in 1252, when Alexander Nevsky accepted an official document, called yarlyk, from Khan Batyj of the Golden Horde (part of the Mongolian Empire), allowing him to reign as the Grand Prince of Kiev (and thus the ruler of all of Russia), rather than ask for a blessing from the Pope in Rome, as was required of all Western kings. To these Western potentates, their claim to be ordained by God was based on approval by His head office at the Vatican; to the Russians, the Pope was just some heretic usurper. The religious distinction played itself out over time, but the notion that there is an exclusive club of Western nations who deserve to wield authority over the rest of the world has remained to this day.

There followed a series of onslaughts on Russia spanning many centuries, all stemming from the same simple principle: that which the West cannot control must be destroyed. The Germans and the Swedes kept on attacking it until 1709. Then the French attacked again in 1812; and then the Germans in 1941. The Americans were poised to attack in March of 2022, via their Ukrainian/NATO proxies, but were preempted by Russia‚Äôs Special Military Operation. Thus, the last Crusade has been aborted and further attempts seem unlikely, since, at this point, there is no question of destroying that which the West cannot control, and not just Russia but also much of the rest of the world. Even tiny North Korea can stand up to the collective West and wag a finger in its face. The thousand-year show is nearly over.

Over the previous centuries, every time after Russia expelled yet another crusader, some other Western nations would take the lead and attempt to march on Moscow: it was the Germans (as the Teutonic Knights, then the Swedes, the Poles, then some more Swedes, then the French under Napoleon, then the Germans under Hitler, and now the Americans (disguised as some hapless, clueless Ukrainians) under Biden. (Yes, the last act of this drama is most definitely a farce.) But who could possibly rise up as the next crusader du Jour? Nobody!
